2006	\begin{proof}
2007	  \uses{def:gr_glued_scheme, lem:gr_separated, def:gr_transition}
2008	  Since \(\mathrm{Gr}(r,d) \to \Spec \mathbb{Z}\) is of finite type
2009	  (\cref{def:gr_glued_scheme}) and separated (\cref{lem:gr_separated}), and
2010	  \(\mathbb{Z}\) is Noetherian, properness follows from the valuative criterion
2011	  for discrete valuation rings: it suffices to show that every solid diagram
2012	  \[
2013	    \begin{array}{ccc}
2014	      \Spec K & \xrightarrow{\ \varphi\ } & \mathrm{Gr}(r,d) \\
2015	      \downarrow & & \downarrow \pi \\
2016	      \Spec R & \longrightarrow & \Spec \mathbb{Z}
2017	    \end{array}
2018	  \]
2019	  with \(R\) a discrete valuation ring, \(K = \operatorname{Frac}(R)\) and
2020	  valuation \(\nu : K \to \mathbb{Z} \cup \{\infty\}\), admits a unique diagonal
2021	  filler \(\Spec R \to \mathrm{Gr}(r,d)\).
2022	
2023	  \emph{Existence.} The morphism \(\varphi : \Spec K \to \mathrm{Gr}(r,d)\) lands
2024	  in some chart \(U^I\) (\(\Spec K\) has one point), so it is given by a ring map
2025	  \(f : \mathbb{Z}[X^I] \to K\). Among the \(\binom{r}{d}\) minors choose \(J\)
2026	  with \(\nu(f(P^I_J))\) minimal. Because \(P^I_I = 1\) gives \(f(P^I_I) = 1\)
2027	  with \(\nu = 0\), the minimum satisfies \(\nu(f(P^I_J)) \le 0\); in particular
2028	  \(f(P^I_J) \ne 0\), so \(f(X^I_J) \in \mathrm{GL}_d(K)\) is invertible over
2029	  \(K\). Define
2030	  \[
2031	    g : \mathbb{Z}[X^J] \longrightarrow K, \qquad
2032	    g(X^J) = f\bigl((X^I_J)^{-1} X^I\bigr) ;
2033	  \]
2034	  this is the composite of \(\theta_{I,J}\) (\cref{def:gr_transition}) with
2035	  \(f\), so \(g\) defines the same \(K\)-point \(\varphi\), now exhibited as
2036	  landing in \(U^J\).
2037	
2038	  We show every entry \(g(x^J_{p,q})\) lies in \(R\), i.e.\ has \(\nu \ge 0\).
2039	  First, for any size-\(d\) subset \(K' \subseteq \{1,\dots,r\}\) the \(K'\)-minor
2040	  of \((X^I_J)^{-1} X^I\) is \((X^I_J)^{-1} X^I_{K'}\), so
2041	  \[
2042	    g(P^J_{K'}) = \det f\bigl((X^I_J)^{-1} X^I_{K'}\bigr)
2043	    = \frac{f(P^I_{K'})}{f(P^I_J)},
2044	    \qquad
2045	    \nu(g(P^J_{K'})) = \nu(f(P^I_{K'})) - \nu(f(P^I_J)) \ge 0
2046	  \]
2047	  by minimality of \(\nu(f(P^I_J))\). Now the \(J\)-minor \(X^J_J\) of \(X^J\) is
2048	  the identity, so by cofactor expansion each individual entry
2049	  \(x^J_{p,q}\) (with \(q \notin J\)) equals, up to sign, the minor
2050	  \(P^J_{K'}\) for \(K' = (J \setminus \{j_p\}) \cup \{q\}\) -- the \(d \times d\)
2051	  determinant obtained by replacing the \(p\)-th identity column of \(X^J_J\) by
2052	  the column \(q\). Hence \(\nu(g(x^J_{p,q})) = \nu(g(P^J_{K'})) \ge 0\) for all
2053	  entries, and the entries with \(q \in J\) are \(0\) or \(1\). Therefore
2054	  \(g(\mathbb{Z}[X^J]) \subseteq R\), so \(g\) factors uniquely as
2055	  \(\mathbb{Z}[X^J] \to R \hookrightarrow K\). The corresponding morphism
2056	  \(\Spec R \to U^J \hookrightarrow \mathrm{Gr}(r,d)\) restricts to \(\varphi\)
2057	  over \(\Spec K\) and lies over \(\Spec \mathbb{Z}\), providing the filler.
2058	
2059	  \emph{Uniqueness.} Any two fillers agree over the generic point \(\Spec K\)
2060	  and, \(\mathrm{Gr}(r,d)\) being separated over \(\mathbb{Z}\)
2061	  (\cref{lem:gr_separated}), two morphisms \(\Spec R \to \mathrm{Gr}(r,d)\)
2062	  agreeing on the schematically dense open \(\Spec K\) coincide. This verifies
2063	  the valuative criterion, so \(\pi : \mathrm{Gr}(r,d) \to \Spec \mathbb{Z}\) is
2064	  proper.
2065	\end{proof}
